\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a multidisciplinary practice led research through practice (practice
 as an element of the research design).
 This concept is an adaptation of the classification that Frayling defines
 in visual arts (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "frayling1993research"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The methodology is based on the study and lessons learnt from a number of
 text visualisation tools that will be developed as part of the project
 artifacts.
 Following Linda Candy (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "candy_practice-led_2006"

\end_inset

), since the main focus of this research is to advance knowledge about practice
 and it seeks to learn about practice through making the artefacts it can
 be considered a practice led research rather than a practice-based one,
 where the contribution to knowledge is demonstrated through artefacts such
 as images, music, designs, models, software.
 For this reason the project cycle reword for each artifact’s development
 is critical.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The developments involve not only computer science knowledge, but team and
 project management, and collaborative design.
 Researchers and professionals from a wide range of disciplines will work
 together, forming temporary teams of development.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several successful cases of data visualisation developments and software
 development in general have influenced the chosen methodology for this
 research project.
 Through my endeavour to work with inspiring people, I am inspired, among
 others, by: Moritz Stefaner: artist & developer that works as a freelance
 from Germany (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "stefaner_m_2013"

\end_inset

), Stamen studio: maps specialists from L.A.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "stamen_2013"

\end_inset

), And in general all kinds of hackerspaces and community labs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These examples share several characteristics:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Size is important:you can work effectively in small or very small teams
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "nualart_2004"

\end_inset

) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Dialogue design: the project design is the result of the communication between
 the developers team and the so-called customer.
 Communication is critical in collaborative project.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Multidisciplinarity: the participants in each project come from a number
 of backgrounds and/or skills.
 There is always presence of people from science and humanities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Freelance culture: they look more like a creative studio, arty, maybe hipster
 than a computer systems corporation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two more examples have inspired this project.
 First: the way that education is evolving in Finland.
 How important is the level of challenge in the motivation of students or
 developers, and how the free knowledge way works better that the proprietary
 one (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "salah_2012"

\end_inset

).
 Second: William J Turkel and his great book “Programming Historian” (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "turkel2007programming"

\end_inset

).
 Turkel is a digital humanities developer that shows cleverly how computing
 can help humanities -historians- on managing and analysing data.
 This is a touchable example of the unavoidable multidisciplinarity of nowadays
 knowledge contribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The analysis and the comparison of each developed case will be the base
 to propose a concrete development methodology that can contribute to increase
 the use of text visualisation tools in real case scenarios.
